# Page Navigation Motion

When implementing routing or page changes, always animate the page content out before navigating away and animate incoming page content in.

## Required implementation

- Use Framer Motion for route transitions (`AnimatePresence` + `motion.*`).
- Wrap route-level page content in `AnimatePresence` so exit animations run on unmount.
- Provide `initial`, `animate`, and `exit` states for page containers.
- Respect reduced motion with `useReducedMotion` and disable transitions when reduction is preferred.
- Keep animations scoped to page content; persistent chrome (e.g., app shell/nav/sidebar) should not unintentionally animate on every route change.

## Example pattern

```tsx
import { AnimatePresence, motion, useReducedMotion } from 'framer-motion';

const variants = {
  initial: { opacity: 0, y: 12 },
  animate: { opacity: 1, y: 0 },
  exit: { opacity: 0, y: -8 },
};

function RoutedPage({ routeKey, children }) {
  const reduce = useReducedMotion();
  const transition = reduce ? { duration: 0 } : { duration: 0.35 };

  return (
    <AnimatePresence mode="wait">
      <motion.main
        key={routeKey}
        variants={variants}
        initial="initial"
        animate="animate"
        exit="exit"
        transition={transition}
      >
        {children}
      </motion.main>
    </AnimatePresence>
  );
}
```
